                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="verdana" size="2" color="white"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> "Fair" as a concept is  mungable to your pre-conceptions of what equitable treatment implies. To use it, without some serious exposition, as the  basis for which one accepts or rejects a reward system (and that is what rolling on loot is) demonstrates a failure to grasp that this one word carries a lot of subjective weight.<br /><br />NBG is "fair" in the sense that those who can use an item are given preference to the item.<br /><br />NBG is not "fair" in the sense that those who work hardest on their gear are precluded from recieving a reward.<br /><br />No one system is going to please everyone all the time, and that's fine.<br /><br />If you don't like NBG don't join NBG groups. If you want a FFA group, start your own if one is  not available. But bitching about "fairness" is silly. NBG is both fair and unfair and so is FFA. All systems have their positives and negatives.<br /><br />Lastly, and just 'cause the irony is wonderful, posting complaining about other's ignorance when you demonstrate a complete lack of understand of the conceptual breadth of the term your using, and justifying calling others ignorant because you "know [you're] rite (sic)" is a great way to end a post. It does leave the audience in stitches.<br /></span id="msg"></font></td>
                    </tr>
